Now, with the rising commodities, energies and raw materials prices, U.S. consumer prices in June posted their biggest jump in over four decades, rising 9.1% on a yearly basis. This is alongside many major economies which have once again set historical inflation rates. In contrast, China's CPI has been maintained in a stable range. While the global inflation rates are in full swing, what makes China the outlier? In this episode of BizBeat, CGTN's Lily Lyu explains why.